Key Insights & Analysis

  • Health Impact: Average of 39.0 estimated respiratory cases per day
  • Pollution Levels: PM2.5 average of 38.1 µg/m³ (exceeds WHO guidelines)
  • Primary Correlate: PM2.5 (ug/m3) shows strongest correlation (r = 0.518)
  • Data Quality: 100.0% complete

Key Characteristics

  • Global financial center ($140-278B GDP). World-class medical tourism hub
  • Extreme wealth inequality (richest city, 55% slums). Rising respiratory disease burden from air quality.
  • Healthcare staff crisis despite best infrastructure
  • Mumbai showcases how extreme urban inequality creates health challenges even in the world's wealthiest cities
    •

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

  • Population: ~22.1M (metro), ~12.7M (city); literacy 89.78%; extremely high density; financial capital of India
  • Respiratory Disease: Rising burden—30-40% surge in winter respiratory infections; upper respiratory tract infections, bronchitis, asthma, COPD common; air quality deterioration major factor
  • Healthcare: India's best infrastructure—16 municipal hospitals, 4 medical colleges, 162 dispensaries; major medical tourism hub; but 26% shortage of healthcare workers, 44% shortage of doctors
  • Seasonal Patterns: 30-40% spike in respiratory illnesses during winter and post-monsoon; humid conditions after rainfall increase viral spread
  • Socioeconomic: GDP $140-278B; richest Indian city (12th globally); net worth ~$1 trillion; contributes 6.16% of national GDP; 55% live in slums despite wealth
